 <div id=bodyContent class=content><div id=mw-content-text dir=ltr class=mw-content-ltr lang=en><div class=mw-parser-output><section class=mf-section-0 id=mf-section-0>
<p>The following is a defined list of terms which are used to describe <a href=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leaf title=Leaf>leaf</a> <a href=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plant_morphology title="Plant morphology">morphology</a> in the description and <a href=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taxonomy_(biology) title="Taxonomy (biology)">taxonomy</a> of plants. Leaves may be simple (a single leaf blade or lamina) or compound (with several <a href=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leaflet_(botany) title="Leaflet (botany)">leaflets</a>). The edge of the leaf may be regular or irregular, may be smooth or bearing hair, bristles or spines. For more terms describing other aspects of leaves besides their overall morphology see the <a href=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leaf#Terminology title=Leaf>leaf</a> article.
<p>The terms listed here all are supported by technical and professional usage, but they cannot be represented as mandatory or undebatable; readers must use their judgement. Authors often use terms arbitrarily, or coin them to taste, possibly in ignorance of established terms, and it is not always clear whether because of ignorance, or personal preference, or because usages change with time or context, or because of variation between specimens, even specimens from the same plant. For example, whether to call leaves on the same tree "acuminate", "lanceolate", or "linear" could depend on individual judgement, or which part of the tree one collected them from. The same cautions might apply to "caudate", "cuspidate", and "mucronate", or to "crenate", "dentate", and "serrate".
<p>Another problem is to establish definitions that meet all cases or satisfy all authorities and readers. For example, it seems altogether reasonable to define a mucro as "a small sharp point as a continuation of the midrib", but it may not be clear how small is small enough, how sharp is sharp enough, how hard the point must be, and what to call the point when one cannot tell whether the leaf has a midrib at all. Various authors or field workers might come to incompatible conclusions, or might try to compromise by qualifying terms so vaguely that a description of a particular plant practically loses its value.
</p>

</section><h2 class="section-heading collapsible-heading open-block"><div class="mw-ui-icon mw-ui-icon-mf-expand mw-ui-icon-element mw-ui-icon-small mf-mw-ui-icon-rotate-flip indicator mw-ui-icon-flush-left"></div><span class=mw-headline id=Leaf_structure tabindex=0 role=button aria-controls=content-collapsible-block-0 aria-expanded=true>Leaf structure</span><span class=mw-editsection><a href="https://en.m.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_leaf_morphology&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Leaf structure" data-section=1 class="mw-ui-icon mw-ui-icon-element mw-ui-icon-wikimedia-edit-base20 edit-page mw-ui-icon-flush-right">Edit</a></span></h2><section class="mf-section-1 collapsible-block open-block" id=content-collapsible-block-0>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class=thumbinner style=width:222px><a href=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Leaf_morphology_type_ternately-compound_palmate-ternate_sessile.png class=image><noscript class=sf-hidden><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/60/Leaf_morphology_type_ternately-compound_palmate-ternate_sessile.png" decoding="async" width="220" height="210" class="thumbimage" data-file-width="220" data-file-height="210"></noscript><img class="thumbimage image-lazy-loaded" alt usemap=undefined style=width:220px;height:210px width=220 height=210></a> <div class=thumbcaption><div class="magnify sf-hidden"></div>A ternate compound leaf with a <a href=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petiole_(botany) title="Petiole (botany)">petiole</a> but no <a href=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rachis title=Rachis>rachis</a> (or rachillae)</div></div></div>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class=thumbinner style=width:222px><a href=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Bipinnate_leaf_anatomy_with_alternate_labels.jpg class=image><noscript class=sf-hidden><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b1/Bipinnate_leaf_anatomy_with_alternate_labels.jpg/220px-Bipinnate_leaf_anatomy_with_alternate_labels.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="220" class="thumbimage" data-file-width="2381" data-file-height="2381"></noscript><img class="thumbimage image-lazy-loaded" alt usemap=undefined style=width:220px;height:220px width=220 height=220></a> <div class=thumbcaption><div class="magnify sf-hidden"></div>Bipinnate leaf anatomy with labels showing alternative usages</div></div></div>
<p>Leaves of most plants include a flat structure called the blade or lamina, but not all leaves are flat, some are cylindrical. Leaves may be simple, with a single leaf blade, or compound, with several <a href=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leaflet_(botany) title="Leaflet (botany)">leaflets</a>. In <a href=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flowering_plants class=mw-redirect title="Flowering plants">flowering plants</a>, as well as the blade of the leaf, there may be a <a href=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petiole_(botany) title="Petiole (botany)">petiole</a> and <a href=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stipule title=Stipule>stipules</a>; compound leaves may have a <a href=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rachis title=Rachis>rachis</a> supporting the leaflets. Leaf structure is described by several terms that include:

<p>Being one of the more visible features, leaf shape is commonly used for plant identification. Similar terms are used for other plant parts, such as <a href=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petal title=Petal>petals</a>, <a href=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tepal title=Tepal>tepals</a>, and <a href=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bract title=Bract>bracts</a>.
</p>

<tr><td><a href=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Leaf_morphology_cuneate.png class=image><noscript class=sf-hidden><img alt="Leaf morphology cuneate.png" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cf/Leaf_morphology_cuneate.png/64px-Leaf_morphology_cuneate.png" decoding="async" width="64" height="24" data-file-width="192" data-file-height="71"></noscript><img class=image-lazy-loaded alt="Leaf morphology cuneate.png" usemap=undefined style=width:64px;height:24px src="data:image/png;base64," srcset sizes width=64 height=24></a></td>

<td>With a sharp, elongated, rigid tip; tipped with a cusp.

<td>Shaped like Greek letter <a href=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Delta_(letter) title="Delta (letter)">Delta</a>, triangular, stem attaches to side.
<tr><td><a href=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Leaf_morphology_digitate.png class=image><noscript class=sf-hidden><img alt="Leaf morphology digitate.png" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4a/Leaf_morphology_digitate.png/64px-Leaf_morphology_digitate.png" decoding="async" width="64" height="39" data-file-width="192" data-file-height="118"></noscript><img class=image-lazy-loaded alt="Leaf morphology digitate.png" usemap=undefined style=width:64px;height:39px src="data:image/png;base64," srcset sizes width=64 height=39></a></td>
<td><span id=digitate>digitate</span></td>
<td><i title="Latin language text" lang=la>digitatus</i></td>
<td>entire leaf</td>
<td>With finger-like lobes, similar to <a href=#palmate>palmate</a>.<sup id=cite_ref-2 class=reference><a href=#cite_note-2>[2]</a></sup><tr><td><a href=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Leaf_morphology_elliptic.png class=image><noscript class=sf-hidden><img alt="Leaf morphology elliptic.png" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8f/Leaf_morphology_elliptic.png/64px-Leaf_morphology_elliptic.png" decoding="async" width="64" height="29" data-file-width="192" data-file-height="88"></noscript><img class=image-lazy-loaded alt="Leaf morphology elliptic.png" usemap=undefined style=width:64px;height:29px src="data:image/png;base64," srcset sizes width=64 height=29></a></td>
<td><span id=elliptic>elliptic</span></td>
<td><i title="Latin language text" lang=la>ellipticus</i></td>
<td>entire leaf</td>
<td>Oval, with a short or no point.
<tr><td><a href=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Leaf_morphology_ensiforme.PNG class=image><noscript class=sf-hidden><img alt="Leaf morphology ensiforme.PNG" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0c/Leaf_morphology_ensiforme.PNG/64px-Leaf_morphology_ensiforme.PNG" decoding="async" width="64" height="10" data-file-width="400" data-file-height="60"></noscript><img class=image-lazy-loaded alt="Leaf morphology ensiforme.PNG" usemap=undefined style=width:64px;height:10px src=data:image/png;base64, srcset sizes width=64 height=10></a></td>
<td><span id=ensiform>ensiform</span></td>
<td><i title="Latin language text" lang=la>ensiformis</i></td>
<td>entire leaf</td>
<td>Shaped like a sword, long and narrow with a sharp pointed tip.

</td>

<td>entire leaf</td>
<td><a href=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sickle title=Sickle>Sickle</a>-shaped.

<tr><td><a href=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Plant_morphology_solid_filiform.png class=image><noscript class=sf-hidden><img alt="Plant morphology solid filiform.png" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0f/Plant_morphology_solid_filiform.png/64px-Plant_morphology_solid_filiform.png" decoding="async" width="64" height="98" data-file-width="104" data-file-height="160"></noscript><img class=image-lazy-loaded alt="Plant morphology solid filiform.png" usemap=undefined style=width:64px;height:98px src=data:image/png;base64, srcset sizes width=64 height=98></a></td>

<td><span id=hastate>hastate</span></td>
<td><i title="Latin language text" lang=la>hastatus</i></td>
<td>entire leaf</td>

<tr><td><a href=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Leaf_morphology_lanceolate.png class=image><noscript class=sf-hidden><img alt="Leaf morphology lanceolate.png" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6e/Leaf_morphology_lanceolate.png/64px-Leaf_morphology_lanceolate.png" decoding="async" width="64" height="17" data-file-width="192" data-file-height="51"></noscript><img class=image-lazy-loaded alt="Leaf morphology lanceolate.png" usemap=undefined style=width:64px;height:17px src="data:image/png;base64," srcset sizes width=64 height=17></a></td>

<td><span id=laminar>laminar</span></td>

</td>
<td>Flat (like most leaves)

<tr><td><a href=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Leaf_morphology_lobed.png class=image><noscript class=sf-hidden><img alt="Leaf morphology lobed.png" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2b/Leaf_morphology_lobed.png/64px-Leaf_morphology_lobed.png" decoding="async" width="64" height="42" data-file-width="192" data-file-height="126"></noscript><img class=image-lazy-loaded alt="Leaf morphology lobed.png" usemap=undefined style=width:64px;height:42px src=data:image/png;base64, srcset sizes width=64 height=42></a></td>

<td><i title="Latin language text" lang=la>lobatus</i></td>

<td>Being divided by clefts, may be pinnately lobed or palmately lobed.
<tr><td><a href=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Leaf_morphology_Lorate.png class=image><noscript class=sf-hidden><img alt="Leaf morphology Lorate.png" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9c/Leaf_morphology_Lorate.png/64px-Leaf_morphology_Lorate.png" decoding="async" width="64" height="15" data-file-width="500" data-file-height="115"></noscript><img class=image-lazy-loaded alt="Leaf morphology Lorate.png" usemap=undefined style=width:64px;height:15px src="data:image/png;base64," srcset sizes width=64 height=15></a></td>

<td><i title="Latin language text" lang=la>loratus</i></td>
<td>entire leaf</td>
<td>Having the form of a thong or strap.
<tr><td><a href=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Leaf_morphology_Lyrate.png class=image><noscript class=sf-hidden><img alt="Leaf morphology Lyrate.png" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Leaf_morphology_Lyrate.png/64px-Leaf_morphology_Lyrate.png" decoding="async" width="64" height="21" data-file-width="500" data-file-height="167"></noscript><img class=image-lazy-loaded alt="Leaf morphology Lyrate.png" usemap=undefined style=width:64px;height:21px src=data:image/png;base64, srcset sizes width=64 height=21></a></td>

<td><i title="Latin language text" lang=la>lyratus</i></td>

<tr><td><a href=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Leaf_morphology_Mucronate.png class=image><noscript class=sf-hidden><img alt="Leaf morphology Mucronate.png" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/12/Leaf_morphology_Mucronate.png/64px-Leaf_morphology_Mucronate.png" decoding="async" width="64" height="54" data-file-width="198" data-file-height="167"></noscript><img class=image-lazy-loaded alt="Leaf morphology Mucronate.png" usemap=undefined style=width:64px;height:54px src="data:image/png;base64," srcset sizes width=64 height=54></a></td>

<td><i>mucronatus</i>
</td>

<td>Ending abruptly in a small sharp point as a continuation of the midrib.<sup id=cite_ref-3 class=reference><a href=#cite_note-3>[3]</a></sup><tr><td><a href=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Leaf_morphology_multifide.svg class=image><noscript class=sf-hidden><img alt="Leaf morphology multifide.svg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/94/Leaf_morphology_multifide.svg/64px-Leaf_morphology_multifide.svg.png" decoding="async" width="64" height="46" data-file-width="278" data-file-height="198"></noscript><img class=image-lazy-loaded alt="Leaf morphology multifide.svg" usemap=undefined style=width:64px;height:46px src=data:image/png;base64, srcset sizes width=64 height=46></a></td>

<td>entire leaf</td>
<td>Lobes spread radially from a point. <sup id=cite_ref-5 class=reference><a href=#cite_note-5>[5]</a></sup><tr><td><a href=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Palmatifide.svg class=image><noscript class=sf-hidden><img alt="Palmatifide.svg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c9/Palmatifide.svg/64px-Palmatifide.svg.png" decoding="async" width="64" height="58" data-file-width="165" data-file-height="149"></noscript><img class=image-lazy-loaded alt=Palmatifide.svg usemap=undefined style=width:64px;height:58px src="data:image/png;base64," srcset sizes width=64 height=58></a></td>

</table></section><h2 class="section-heading collapsible-heading open-block"><div class="mw-ui-icon mw-ui-icon-mf-expand mw-ui-icon-element mw-ui-icon-small mf-mw-ui-icon-rotate-flip indicator mw-ui-icon-flush-left"></div><span class=mw-headline id=Edge tabindex=0 role=button aria-controls=content-collapsible-block-2 aria-expanded=true>Edge</span><span class=mw-editsection><a href="https://en.m.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Glossary_of_leaf_morphology&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Edge" data-section=3 class="mw-ui-icon mw-ui-icon-element mw-ui-icon-wikimedia-edit-base20 edit-page mw-ui-icon-flush-right">Edit</a></span></h2><section class="mf-section-3 collapsible-block open-block" id=content-collapsible-block-2>
<p>Leaf margins (edges) are frequently used in visual plant identification because they are usually consistent within a species or group of species, and are an easy characteristic to observe. Edge and margin are interchangeable in the sense that they both refer to the outside perimeter of a leaf.
</p>

<p>Leaves may also be folded or rolled in various ways. If the leaves are initially folded in the bud, but later unrolls it is called <a href=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vernation title=Vernation>vernation</a>, <a href=https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/ptyxis class=extiw title=wikt:ptyxis>ptyxis</a> is the folding of an individual leaf in a bud.
</p>

<p>The Latin word for 'leaf', <i title="Latin language text" lang=la>folium</i>, is neuter. In descriptions of a single leaf, the neuter singular ending of the adjective is used, e.g. <i title="Latin language text" lang=la>folium lanceolatum</i> 'lanceolate leaf', <i title="Latin language text" lang=la>folium lineare</i> 'linear leaf'. In descriptions of multiple leaves, the neuter plural is used, e.g. <i title="Latin language text" lang=la>folia linearia</i> 'linear leaves'. Descriptions commonly refer to the plant using the ablative singular or plural, e.g. <i title="Latin language text" lang=la>foliis ovatis</i> 'with ovate leaves'.<sup id=cite_ref-FOOTNOTEStearn2004439â€“440_7-0 class=reference><a href=#cite_note-FOOTNOTEStearn2004439%E2%80%93440-7>[7]</a></sup></p>
